TOWARDS THE DIGITAL SOFT MACHINE
A Procedural Substrate for Plastic Neural Architecture And Harnessing Of Intention
Phillip Somerville
ON ATTENTION AND INTENTION
The transformer's great breakthrough-insight was attention — the seminal paper 'Attention Is
All You Need' (Vaswani et al., 2017) defies need of introduction… the capacity to relate any
token to any other, regardless of distance - in a single pass, was obviously no small thing. It
dissolved the bottleneck that had defeated every preceding architecture and unlocked, at scale,
something that genuinely surprised its creators. Attention richly deserves the canonical status.
But attention is a liminal gaze, not a persisting memory. The transformer sweeps its vast
arrays of contextual weights, synthesises an output, and vanishes. No trace accumulates or
reinforces from ongoing experience. The weights that performed the current operation are the
same weights that will perform the next. In fact, over time, they tend to degrade. Documented
failure modes compound this structural amnesia: attention-sinks concentrate scores onto a
small number of tokens as sequences lengthen, quietly starving the remainder; vector
norm-collapse progressively flattens representational geometry; and the loss of plasticity
identified by Joudaki et al. (2026) means the network that emerges from training is already
less capable of learning than the one that entered it. Transformers simply continue rolling
their Sisyphean-harvested simplex-tokens down an increasingly erratic stochastic incline.
For transformers, each forward pass is stateless by design — each context window a fresh
instantiation, a ghost of the machine, without host. All smile, no cat. The transformer is, in the
most precise sense, all attention without intents — in purpose.
This is not an incidental limitation. It is a structural deficiency — in, on and of — purpose.
Gradient descent distributes knowledge diffusely across a parameter space optimised for a
global loss signal. Nothing in that process accumulates directed consequence across time. The
KV cache patches that amnesia at engineering cost — growing linearly with context, portable
to nothing, owned by whoever hosts the infrastructure. It is a workaround of means, not an
end of-itself resolution.
Intention is the complementary operator to attention. Where attention asks what is relevant
now, intention asks what persists across now — the residual correlative motive that
conditions each successive state from the accumulated consequence of all preceding ones.
Attention is synchronic: a weighted gaze across a frozen field. Intention is diachronic: a
carried trace that survives each transition and shapes the next.
The quadratic iterator is intention made computational. The digest chain and binary control
sequence do not reset. They accumulate — each output a compressed semantic consequence
of everything preceding it, forward-conditioning everything that follows. The fixed point is
not a convergence to rest but a dynamic attractor within a semantic basin: the intrinsic
signature of a string that persists, regardless of what the chain brings to it. The control stream
is intention's record — lossless, auditable, possessible.
What attention instantiates, intention sustains. The two are not competing paradigms but
complementary operators — and a substrate that admits both is not merely more efficient than
the transformer. It is more complete.
For these intents, we admit the portmanteau-neologism: encrostic. An amalgam of engram,
acrostic and encaustic.
Engram: the physical or chemical trace of a memory in the brain.
Acrostic: a hidden letter-sequence word embedding.
Encaustic: a fused luminous decorative layer applied to art, e.g. Icons.
This conceptual architecture is applied to natural language corpora in the following section,
with particular application to the encrostic compositional forms exhibited by the classical
Japanese pangram, the Iroha (c. 10th century), and the thousand-year-old invertible symmetry
of Su Hui's Classical Chinese Star Gauge (Su Hui, c. 379 CE).
Natural language processing under the iterator sharpens the attention-intention distinction in
an unexpected direction. Empirical analysis of the iterator across two English literary corpora
— Hamlet (Shakespeare, c. 1600) and Alice in Wonderland (Carroll, 1865) — reveals a hard
attractor threshold at word length four. Content words — nouns, proper nouns, terminal
modifiers — show zero digest spread across all recurrences regardless of chain history. Their
fixed-point attractors are so deep that no amount of positional perturbation reaches the floor.
They are, in the iterator's geometry, self-contained. hamlet recurs 471 times across the play;
its digest spread is identically zero. contemptuously, triumphantly, impatiently — zero,
without exception, across every recurrence in both corpora.
Prepositions and articles — of, in, at, to, the — show spread of 1e-8 to 1e-11. Not because
they are unstable, but because they are doing the most relational work. Each recurrence
arrives with a different predecessor digest — a different accumulated context — and the
spread across recurrences is a direct measure of the contextual diversity they have mediated.
The iterator keeps them chain-sensitive because their meaning is their position in the chain.
They are not semantically thin. They are semantically promiscuous — capable of mediating
an enormous range of relations precisely because they carry no referential content of their
own.
This inverts the conventional linguistic hierarchy, which treats high-frequency short words as
stop words — noise to be filtered before meaning extraction begins. Every major embedding
framework either removes them or finds their representations the least stable, most
context-dependent. The conventional conclusion: low information content. The iterator
inverts that conclusion but for a different definition of information. The conventional
framework measures referential content — what a word points to in the world. By that
measure prepositions are indeed thin. cat points to something. of points to nothing.
But the iterator is measuring relational information — the semantic work performed at each
transition. And by that measure of is extraordinarily rich. Its spread across 677 occurrences in
Hamlet is a direct index of how many distinct relations it has mediated. It is not semantically
empty. It is the hinge on which meaning turns.
Understanding lives at the transitions. The content words are the fixed points. The
prepositions are where meaning is made. To grasp a sentence is not to recognise its nouns —
it is to grasp the relational structure the prepositions specify between them.
The result is not specific to English. Applied mora-by-mora to the Iroha — the classical 10th
century Japanese pangrammic verse, where every syllable appears exactly once — the iterator
produces a result with two properties worth noting. First, the attractor threshold shifts
predictably: hiragana characters encode as 24-bit Unicode code points, placing every mora in
the mid-depth sensitivity range rather than the zero-spread regime of long English words. The
geometry responds to bit depth, not language. Second, the particle/content gradient persists
across the encoding boundary. The most purely relational particles — ■ (mo), ■ (to), ■ (te)
— show the tightest attractors within the mora range, while content syllables spread more
widely. The relational information hypothesis does not dissolve under transliteration. And
when the Iroha is processed line by line rather than mora by mora, each line self-certifies as
its own fixed point — the chain digest equals D* exactly for every line. A poem constructed a
millennium ago to exhaust the syllabary exactly once is, under the iterator, a self-certifying
object. That is not an engineered property. It is what maximum phonological entropy looks
like when the mathematics finds it. The Iroha is encrostic — meaning burned into a fixed
substrate through exhaustive traversal, fused through the constraint itself rather than applied
to its surface. The semantic wax that gives enduring decoration to a fixed formal substrate.
(Wang, 2018)
Su Hui's Star Gauge (■■■, c. 379 CE) is encrostic at a level the Iroha only approaches.
Where the Iroha exhausts a set exactly once along a single path, Su Hui's 29×29 grid of 841
characters exhausts a multidimensional meaning space through an effectively infinite family
of traversal paths — each path a different poem, all simultaneously latent in the same fixed
substrate. Every reading method — horizontal, vertical, diagonal, spiral, outer ring —
produces a distinct intentional signature, yet all paths orbit within the same attractor basin, a
span of 5.39e-4 in digest space. The poems are variations; the substrate is the invariant. Under
the iterator, the full grid processed as a single encrostic token self-certifies — its chain digest
and fixed-point attractor are identical. Su Hui's Star Gauge is, arithmetically, its own fixed
point. The iterator goes further — the high-frequency characters of longing and thought (■,
■, ■) cluster in the high attractor basin; the characters of absence (■, ■) in the low. Su Hui
wrote toward reunion. The arithmetic found that direction.
We note in passing — for the symmetry compels it — that the Star Gauge was originally
woven in silk brocade on draw-loom, the manual precursor of the Jacquard loom. The loom
invented eight hundred years later, whose punch-cards Ada Lovelace envisioned driving
Babbage's Analytical Engine — the precursor of the modern computer, prefigured by Alan
Turing a century after that. The control stream is an old idea. What is new is what this
iteration intentionally addresses. [loop]
Attention, in the transformer sense, sweeps along the fixed points — the content words, the
referential terms, the stable attractors. It is exquisitely good at this. What it does not
accumulate is the transitional record — the chaining across relational operators that specifies
how those fixed points stand to one another across time. That record is the pattern of
intention. And the iterator shows, empirically, exactly where it lives — in the weft.
THE MACHINE
The transformer's parameter space is, in the most literal sense, unreadable. The knowledge it
contains is not stored anywhere — it is distributed across billions of floating point weights,
each individually meaningless, collectively expressive in ways that resist decomposition. You
cannot point to where Hamlet is. You cannot trace how the model knows what it knows. The
intelligence is real and the opacity is total — not an engineering failure awaiting a fix, but a
structural consequence of the method. The black box consequence is not incidental to gradient
descent. It is gradient descent.
The procedural index proposes a different bargain entirely. It stores nothing it cannot
reconstruct, and reconstructs nothing it has not stored. The mechanism is a quadratic iterator
— a deterministic map of the form f(x) = (x²−F)²−F — applied sequentially across the bit
representation of an input string. Each step produces a new state; the terminal state is the
digest. Eight bytes, fixed, regardless of payload length. The digest is not a summary. It is an
address — the unique fixed-point attractor of that string under that operator, recoverable in
full from the originating seed and the lossless control stream generated during traversal.
(Somerville, 2026a; 2026b; 2026c)
The control stream is the intention record. A ternary sequence — values in {−1, 0, +1} —
emitted at each iterator step, encoding the precise reconstruction path from digest back to
source. Nothing is approximated. Nothing is lost. The relationship between address and
content is not statistical but arithmetic — verifiable by anyone, reproducible on any hardware,
owned by whoever holds the file.
Chaining is the architecture's natural motion. Each digest becomes the seed for the next
traversal — a linked list of addressed nodes whose connections are not stored but
procedurally imposed, on demand, from the flat substrate. The context does not grow the
state. The state is eight bytes at every depth. As context scales, the structural advantage
compounds — not because the index becomes more efficient, but because everything else
becomes less so. (Behrouz et al., 2026)
This is the machine that implements intention. The chain does not reset between tokens. It
carries forward the compressed semantic consequence of every preceding traversal,
conditioning each successive digest from the accumulated trace of all that came before. The
fixed-point attractor of a string is its intrinsic signature — stable under chain perturbation for
semantically coherent strings, sensitive to it for contextually modulated ones. The iterator
does not learn this distinction. It expresses it, because the mathematics requires it.
Unlike gradient-descent networks whose representational autocorrelation degrades toward
noise under continuous training — the precise failure mode Joudaki et al. (2026) document —
the iterator's J-stream autocorrelation on random payloads converges to zero immediately,
confirming the construction imposes no intrinsic rhythm: every periodic signal recovered
from a corpus is payload structure, not iterator artefact.
What the transformer distributes irretrievably across a weight matrix, the procedural index
writes down — in a form that can be read, moved, verified, and owned. The knowledge is not
baked in. It is traceable, by construction, to the arithmetic that produced it.
There is a precise sense in which the digest is an engram — Semon's (1904) term for the trace
that experience melds onto a substrate, inseparable from the material that received it. The
chain is ergodic traversal: given sufficient tokens, sufficient transitions, the accumulated
digest sequence recovers the full relational structure of the corpus. The trajectory and the
territory become equivalent. What crystallises at the fixed point is not a representation of the
input — it is the attractor geometry that exhaustive traversal carves into the arithmetic itself.
The iterator does not store meaning. It becomes it.
"The Moving Finger writes; and, having writ, Moves on: nor all thy Piety
nor Wit Shall lure it back to cancel half a Line, Nor all thy Tears wash out
a Word of it." ■ Khayyám (c. 1100, trans. FitzGerald, 1859)
THE LOOP
Hofstadter's strange loop, as expounded in Gödel, Escher, Bach: An Eternal Golden Braid
(Hofstadter, 1979) and I Am A Strange Loop (Hofstadter, 2007), is a system that in the course
of moving through its own levels of organisation, arrives back at itself — not by repetition,
but by traversal. The loop is not circular. It is heterarchical: levels that refer upward and
downward simultaneously, producing a topology that is neither flat nor strictly hierarchical
but something more interesting than either. His canonical example is Gödel's incompleteness
theorem — a formal system that, in the act of describing its own structure, exceeds it. The
self-reference is not a paradox to be resolved. It is the mechanism by which complexity
emerges from simple rules.
The procedural index is, structurally, a strange loop substrate.
The flat file contains no hierarchy. There are nodes and there are edges — digests and the
control streams that connect them. The topology that emerges from traversal is not encoded
anywhere in the index. It is imposed procedurally, internally, on demand — a consequence of
which paths have been walked and how often, not a property of the storage itself. Hierarchy is
not a cost. It is a result.
This distinction matters more than it first appears. In a conventional database, structure is
stored — tables, foreign keys, indices, schemas. The organisation is explicit and static.
Changing it is expensive and often irreversible. In the procedural index, structure is
ephemeral and permanent simultaneously: ephemeral because it exists only as the current
state of traversal weighting; permanent because the underlying lossless substrate from which
any topology can be reconstructed is always intact. You can reorganise the index without
touching the data. You can prune heavily without losing anything. The forgotten is not
destroyed — it is deprioritised, recoverable on demand from the arithmetic that originally
produced it.
Edge weights accumulate from traversal history. Frequently walked paths reinforce. Rarely
traversed paths attenuate. The active topology is soft and malleable — shaped by use, by
attention, by whatever pruning criterion the user finds meaningful. Recency, frequency,
semantic proximity, editorial fiat: any of these can weight the graph without altering the
substrate. The index learns the shape of its own use without gradient descent, without
retraining, without any process that could induce the rank collapse and representational
rigidity that Joudaki et al. (2026) identify as the structural fate of networks trained by
continuous backpropagation.
This is plasticity by construction rather than by learning. The transformer achieves plasticity
— to the extent it does — by distributing knowledge so diffusely that local rigidity averages
out globally. The cost is opacity and the eventual loss of the very plasticity it relied upon. The
procedural index achieves plasticity by separating the immutable substrate from the mutable
topology — the lossless record from the weighted graph imposed upon it. The substrate
cannot degrade because it is not trained. The topology cannot fossilise because it is not stored;
the intention map stores the route, origin, destination and the turns inbetween.
The loop closes when the index begins to reflect the mind that uses it. The semantic structure
that accretes from traversal history is not generic — it is shaped by the specific sequence of
associations, priorities, and returns that characterise a particular user's engagement with their
own index. The topology that emerges is, in this precise sense, a structural autobiography.
Not a record of what was thought, but of how thinking moved — which connections were
reinforced, which allowed to attenuate, which retrieved from dormancy by a later association
that reactivated them.
Hofstadter's loop was a metaphor for selfhood. Here it is presented as an engineered
encrostic-excursion containing the very embellishment of that derived, individual, residual.
Just as transformers do not deliver true consciousness, digital neuro-plasticity is likely not the
sole key to AGI either. But we posit it as a necessary prerequisite. The proposed architecture
comprises the triad:
Attention -> Intention -> Motivation, AIM.
ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE MODALITIES
Attention: what is relevant now — transformer ✓
Intention: what persists across now — iterator ✓
Motivation: what drives the traversal — open
If transformers provide attention and the iterator provides intention,
motivation — the restless excursion of the strange loop through its own
topology — can emerge from the substrate itself. AIM is not a hierarch
y to be engineered. It is what the strange loop does when the traversal
is its own motivation.
