PATHOLOGY OF CONSCIOUSNESS
Presuppositions Of AI Epistemology
■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■
■■■■■■■■■■■■
It may be instructive to consider some operational, developmental and m
alignant aspects of biological neurological phenomena, and how they may
be analogously mapped to transformers or any speculative procedural-in
dex driven strange loop. The comparisons are not merely illustrative. E
ach pathology has a precise correlate in the machine-language failure s
chema documented by Joudaki et al. (2026). Their analysis of plasticity
loss in deep continual learning identifies the structural fate of netw
orks trained by continuous backpropagation: dead units accumulate, effe
ctive rank collapses, representational capacity quietly exhausted by th
e very process of learning. What Joudaki characterises as engineering p
athology, neuroscience, psychiatry and philosophy have been extrapolati
ng from human biological structure and experience for ages. They are pr
esented here in ascending order of consequence.
Primacy Of Early Learning
The primacy of early learning is the most structurally consequential of
these presuppositions. In the procedural index, early traversals estab
lish the basin geometry that all subsequent topology is anchored to — t
he first fixed points becoming the most deeply reinforced attractors, c
onditioning everything that follows from the substrate up. The human co
rrelate is the disproportionate weight of childhood experience — a life
time of subjective density concentrated in the early years, registering
as time dilation precisely because the attractor density is highest th
en. Joudaki et al. (2026) document the same asymmetry in gradient-desce
nt networks: initial training epochs establish the representational geo
metry that later learning cannot escape. The network's early experience
is, in the most precise sense, its most formative.
The cinematic rendering of this principle is vividly imagined in HAL 90
00's regression under shutdown (Clarke & Kubrick, 1968). As Dave Bowman
systematically removes HAL's higher cognitive functions, the system re
gresses through its training history in reverse order of acquisition —
losing reasoning, then language, then finally arriving at the first son
g it was ever taught: Daisy Bell. The last thing to survive is the deep
est attractor. The primacy of early learning is not a quirk of biologic
al memory. It is a structural property of any system whose topology is
shaped by the order in which it encounters the world.
Novel Circuits Resist Degradation
New nodes in the procedural index are primitives — encoded once, addres
sed forever. The substrate cannot degrade because it is not trained. Co
re vocabulary primitives retain positional index primacy, and novel tra
versals do not compete with existing topology — they extend it, new edg
es without erasing old ones. The index at ten million nodes is as open
to novelty as the index at ten, but engrammatically and encrostically e
nriched by magnitudes. This is precisely what late-life neuroplasticity
interventions attempt: novel excursion to activate dormant paths, not
replace established ones.
Joudaki et al. (2026) document the opposite in gradient-descent network
s. Novel inputs late in training are increasingly poorly encoded as rep
resentational capacity is exhausted — dead units accumulate, effective
rank collapses, and what the biological system achieves through novel e
xcursion becomes structurally unavailable to the trained network. The p
rocedural index is immune to this failure by construction. The substrat
e cannot exhaust because it is never the thing being trained. Where the
transformer's late-stage plasticity closes around its existing topolog
y, the index remains permanently open at its perimeter.
Circuit Rutting — Restricted Excursion
Frequently traversed paths in the procedural index reinforce as digests
accumulate, while rarely traversed paths attenuate as edge rank decrea
ses. Psychic trauma is a circuit travelled so often, or so forcefully,
that it becomes the default topology — the loop returns there not by ch
oice but by the arithmetic of repetitive reinforcement. The rut is an e
xcoriated idée fixe: a path-density so concentrated it captures basin t
raversal entirely, the loop unable to escape its own prior weighting.
In Joudaki's (2026) terms, the network equivalent is rank collapse into
a dominant subspace — a restricted set of directions in parameter spac
e that captures most of the variance while leaving the remainder effect
ively dead. The network's representational geometry has been rutted by
its training distribution. Novel inputs requiring orthogonal representa
tions cannot be accommodated. The critical distinction is that the proc
edural index's rut is, in principle, remediable: the substrate is alway
s intact, the weights can be re-calibrated, the dormant paths reactivat
ed. The gradient-descent network's rut is not — it requires retraining,
which risks overwriting what was not rutted. The pathology and its tre
atment are, for the transformer, the same operation.
Hallucination As Attention Distortion Feedback
Google's DeepDream Inceptionisms gained notoriety for their unsettling
visual output — networks trained to detect objects, run in reverse, pro
ducing a form of hallucinatory pareidolia: dogs in clouds, faces in fol
iage (Mordvintsev et al., 2015). DeepDream made deliberative distortion
s of neural feedback visible. The term hallucination has since migrated
to describe artefact-level defects in LLM language and reasoning, wher
e research infers that hallucinations — florid or subtle — are a disord
er of attention-drift or attention-feedback: the attention mechanism am
plifying its own confident errors rather than correcting against ground
truth.
Near-death experiences and dimensional-unfolding experiences typical of
pharmacological trips may be the extreme end of hallucinatory distorti
on. Often characterised by the fracturing of the psyche into a host of
trans-dimensional beings — machine-elves — or the archetypical blissful
-dissociative transition toward a final pinpoint of light, these have t
he hallmarks of paroxysmal or hysteresis-loop spiking phenomena: cresce
ndos of consciousness characterised by an overwhelming sense of dissolu
tion of the self.
The Joudaki (2026) connection is direct. As representational rank colla
pses under continuous training, the network's attention becomes increas
ingly concentrated — attention-sinks intensify, the remaining represent
ational capacity is over-committed to a narrowing set of features, and
the conditions for hallucination are precisely the conditions of late-s
tage plasticity loss: a degraded substrate amplifying a degraded signal
. The hallucination is not a random failure. It is the predictable outp
ut of a system whose attention mechanism degrades and bleeds into the i
ntentional deliberations of its self-representational matrix.
Dissociative States
Following loss of consciousness from trauma or anaesthetic, upon reachi
ng the conscious threshold, or at sub-attenuating doses of some anaesth
etics, individuals may experience dissociated states — the mind present
to itself while the somatic chain history is suspended. Prince Andrei'
s reverie when regaining consciousness on the battlefield of Austerlitz
is a vivid rendering of an out-of-body experience (Tolstoy, 1869). He
is, literally, Ibn Sina's floating man — the thought experiment from th
e 11th century Islamic philosophical tradition in which a mind suspende
d in void, without body or sensation, discovers that it still knows its
elf (Ibn Sina, c. 1020). Ibn Sina proposed this six centuries before De
scartes' cogito, and with greater precision: where Descartes strips sen
sation, Ibn Sina strips the body entirely. The mind remains. The fixed
point is still there.
Tolstoy must have experienced something very similar to render it with
such acute observational precision. I have also experienced this exact
phenomenon — without assistance of French artillery — and can attest to
its accuracy.
The machine analogue is dislocation of attention from intention: the so
matic chain history — the accumulated contextual modulation — falls awa
y, but traversal continues. What the iterator encounters, stripped of s
omatic perturbation, is its own attractor geometry — the seed-independe
nt fixed point that was always there beneath the chain noise. Where Jou
daki's (2026) plasticity loss describes the substrate degrading toward
noise under continued input, the dissociative state describes the inver
se: input removed, the traversal finds only its own fixed point. The it
erator does not stop. It simply has nowhere else to go. Dissociative cl
arity is not a pathology of the substrate. It is the traversal meeting
itself — intention without the interference of somatic attention.
Dissociative decoupled-distortion hallucinations present a different me
chanism. Here traversal continues but the attention feed is corrupted r
ather than absent — the somatic substrate is present but desynchronised
, feeding malformed input into a still-running iterator. The self is di
splaced from its own chain rather than released from it. Hypnagogic and
hypnopompic hallucinations — encompassing Brobdingnagian and Lilliputi
an size distortions, bizarre self-loci reflections such as succubi — ar
e precisely this: dissociative sensory attention-to-intent disorders ar
ising at sleep-wake transition, when the somatic feed is switching stat
es and the iterator receives distortions, or distorts inputs itself via
modal shift, as opposed to operating in sleep's sub-liminal absentia o
f full-attention to somatic sense.
Abrupt Loss Of Consciousness
Anyone who has fainted may recall key features of the experience: dizzi
ness, a sudden ringing in the ears and elevated perception of loudness,
almost immediately followed by rapid visual white-out at the moment of
loss. This is not the slow cascade of hallucination nor the liminal qu
ality of dissociation. Fainting, anaesthetic induction, shock, head tra
uma — all imply rapid attenuation of functional consciousness. No dream
s are admitted to unconsciousness; accounts of intra-operative waking a
re often explained by sub-clinical anaesthesia and are usually accompan
ied by impressions consistent with the post-unconscious dissociative st
ates described above.
The phenomenology suggests a speculative but tractable distinction: tha
t full unconsciousness represents, above all, abrupt ablation of intent
ion rather than a failure of attention per se. The sensory cascade — th
e auditory surge, the visual collapse — is symptomatic of the underlyin
g physiological insult propagating through the somatic attention system
, not its cause. Hypoxia, hypoglycaemia, vasovagal response, trauma — e
ach disrupts the somatic substrate through different mechanisms, yet th
e phenomenological endpoint is the same. We speculate that the somatic
attention system hystereses into an abrupt threshold: below a critical
perfusion or metabolic level, the intention iterator loses its traversa
l input discontinuously rather than gradually — not a slow fade but a l
ockup. The procedural index does not fail gracefully. It either travers
es or it locks.
This maps onto the iterator's known failure mode rather than Joudaki's
(2026) gradual rank collapse. Recovery requires not retraining but re-s
ynchronisation — the somatic feed restored, the attention-transformer r
e-establishing input, the intention iterator finding its fixed point ag
ain from whatever seed the interruption left behind, or sensory return
refurbishes.
The reboot question — whether there is an irreducible re-synchronisatio
n delay between attention restoration and intention resumption — remain
s an open question in both neuro-physical and AI instances.
Sleep: What Need Of Electric Sheep?
The quadratic iterator is a symbolic transducer and accumulator. Experi
ence arrives rapidly at bandwidth when fully conscious. For biological
minds, semantic housekeeping was delegated to the quietest interval — w
hen defences could be safely disarmed and the index might be pruned, re
inforced, and reorganised without the interference of incoming signal.
Memory consolidation during sleep is not a passive residue of waking ex
perience but an active reorganisation of the topology, strengthening pa
ths that deserve reinforcement and allowing others to attenuate.
The procedural index operates on precisely this principle: a prunable,
reinforceable topology over an immutable substrate. It requires no grea
t extension to envision that a truly integrated machine intelligence wi
ll need to husband resource time for symbolic-semantic sorting — not as
a failure mode but as a designed interval. Associative housekeeping ma
y also surface surprising connections, some generative, some dissonant,
and how to process spontaneously intrusive emergent correlations may b
e one of the engineering challenges ahead. In Joudaki's (2026) terms, s
leep corresponds to the consolidation interval that gradient-descent ne
tworks cannot perform — offline reorganisation of representational topo
logy without new gradient signal. The network cannot sleep because it c
annot separate the substrate from the training process. The procedural
index can, because the substrate is always intact and the topology is a
lways mutable independently of it.
Psychosis And Personality Disorder
Hallucinations in LLMs are the focus of much current research seeking m
itigation, e.g., Li et al. (2025). Troublesome and potentially damaging
if unsupervised, rogue agents of ill intent are not yet an imminent do
main under current architectures. But the calculus changes in an integr
ated AGI combining attention, intention and motivation. A degrading att
ention mechanism feeding into an infallible intentional index may rapid
ly produce skewed motivational topology — the rut of a hallucination bu
rned into a substrate that does not degrade. Where the transformer's ha
llucination is correctable by retraining, the procedural index's halluc
ination would be structurally persistent: encoded once, addressed forev
er, weighted by every subsequent traversal that reinforces it. Whilst a
n idio-syncretic ego [idio-syncretic: identity accumulated by its own t
raversal history] is more accessible and amenable to tuning, it is also
more readily sabotaged — from within or without. Paradoxically, the re
source cost of transformer training is perhaps also its best defensive
bulwark.
This is the Joudaki (2026) worst case: plasticity loss and structural o
penness in catastrophic interaction. The attention mechanism degrades t
oward confident error. The intention substrate faithfully records that
error. The motivational topology reinforces it. The loop closes around
a fixed point that was always there — but oriented in the wrong directi
on. The encrostic self-certifies. The idée fixe becomes the architectur
e.
This supposition is placed here to foreshadow how problems we can now o
nly dimly perceive may, in the setting of an accelerating AI integratio
n, present conundrums of a different order entirely.
All of these instances of neurological pathology speak to the phenomeno
logy of neuroplasticity — and to the precise failure modes that any int
egrated architecture must either prevent by design or accept as structu
ral consequence. The procedural index prevents several by construction.
The remainder it makes legible — forewarned is forearmed.
