■■■■■■■■■■■■
DIGITAL DEMOCRACY OR TECHNOLOGICAL FEUDALISM?
'Neither serf nor Luddite be.'
■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■
■■■■■■■■■■■■
The prevailing architecture of AI deployment is, by resource necessity,
centralised. The intelligence resides elsewhere. Your context travels
to it, is processed by it, and returns transformed — usefully, impressi
vely, but always on terms set by the infrastructure that hosts it. Pers
onalisation in this arrangement is a service afforded to you. Your pref
erences, your associations, your accumulated semantic history: propriet
ary parameters, captive to a platform, non-transferable, non-verifiable
, and subject to whatever the terms of service permit on the day you ne
ed them.
Here we return to Alan Turing. His closest friend Christopher Morcom di
ed suddenly in 1930, when Turing was seventeen. In attention of his gri
ef he wrote to Morcom's mother imagining the mind as something that cou
ld persist beyond the body — personification as the 'software of the so
ul' — and in doing so, signalled the intention which delivered us the i
ntellectual framework of modern computing. A sublime motivation. Howeve
r, I can't imagine he envisioned anything so profane as some tawdry sub
scription-memorialisation of his precious soulmate.
This need not be the morbid destiny of abstracted machine intelligence.
The procedural index is, at core, a local primitive. The digest is eigh
t bytes. The control stream is a file. The linked-list topology that ac
cretes from use — weighted by traversal, shaped by attention, pruned by
whatever criteria the user finds meaningful — can be built on whatever
hardware is to hand. There is nothing in the architecture that require
s a data centre. There is no inference cost at retrieval. There is no s
ubscription. The index may be owned in the way a notebook is owned — no
t licensed, not hosted, not meted by tithing of third party tributes.
Provenance follows naturally from the iterator's arithmetic. The canoni
cal fixed-point digest is self-certifying — authenticity is not an anno
tation appended to content but a property verifiable from the index its
elf, by anyone, on any hardware, without appeal to the institution that
issued it. Copyright becomes traceable to first encoding. Blockchain a
ddressability follows from the digest chain's structure — each node's a
ddress a deterministic function of its content and its position in the
chain, immutable and auditable without a trusted intermediary.
What emerges from these properties in combination is not merely an effi
cient storage primitive. It is a substrate whose organisational complex
ity arises not from explicit encoding but from the procedural impositio
n of structure on a flat foundation — relational, self-certifying, dyna
mically prunable, losslessly recoverable, and genuinely portable in a s
ense that no transformer deployment can claim.
The centralised model has produced remarkable things and will continue
to do so. The procedural index does not replace it. But it points in a
different direction — agency over intent. That direction has a name.
It is simply called ownership. All we need now is the motivation.
